nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|1|fp|t|at|
^-{ How the bidding works }
^-|fp||at|
There are 2 main things that happen on every bridge deal, the bidding, which always happens first, followed by the play of the cards. Up until now almost everything we have learned has been about the play of the cards. This should help make it easier for you to get a good grasp of what the bidding is all about.

|
pg| ***** 1 ***** |


cs|4|at|We have already learned enough about bidding to know that it is a very important part of every bridge deal. The bidding determines:

^-{Which player will be the declarer}

|cs|1|at|{Which player will make the opening lead}

|cs|3|at|{What the declarer's trick-winning goal will be}

|cs|2|at|{What the trump suit will be (or if the deal will be played at notrump)}
^-
|
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


at|In this chapter we will have a look at the mechanics of the bidding and how all of the above factors are determined in the bidding. We will also have a look at some strategies that a partnership can use to help facilitate accurate bidding.|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
|st||sk||
md|sajt9h2da32ckjt98,s432hqt54djt9ca43,skq87ha987dq54cQ2|rh||at|The best way to get a feel for the bidding is to watch it happen in a real bridge deal. |
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
On each deal of bridge one player is responsible for shuffling and dealing out the cards. This player is known as the
dealer. The dealer is indicated in the top left corner of the screen by the letter ^*bD^*n (it is South on this deal).|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
The dealer rotates in a clockwise manner around the table. When the bidding and play of the cards of this deal are finished, West, the next player clockwise after South, will be the dealer for the next deal.|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
There is a nice reward that the dealer receives for his job of shuffling and dealing. The dealer is the first player to participate in the bidding.|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
On this deal South is the dealer so he is the first player who has a chance to make a bid.|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


ha||
at|^^ 
What exactly does making a bid consist of ?       Watch...|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


mb|1c|an|The opening bid|
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
You can now see a bidding diagram on your screen with a single bid displayed. South, the dealer, has bid 1@C. 

The first bid is referred to as the opening bid.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
In a real bridge game the bidding is done verbally. South would actually say "one club" out loud, to let the other players at the table know what bid he chose to make.|
pg| ***** 12 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
The bidding, like the play to each trick and the rotation of the dealer, proceeds in a clockwise manner around the table.  Bridge is a very clockwise game.|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
South has bid 1@C and now it is West (the next player sitting clockwise after South) who gets a chance to bid.|
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


mb|p|
nt|^z@3^b@2
This particular West decides not to bid at all at his turn. Instead West chooses to pass and it becomes North's turn to either bid or pass.|
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


cs|1|at|^^^^^-{Each player can either bid or pass at his turn during the bidding.
There is a bit more to it than that, but the above rule is a good one for now.}
|
pg| ***** 16 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
Passes only come in 1 flavor, but there are 35 possible bids a player can make. Each of the 35 possible bids consist of 2 parts:|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


cs|4|at|^^^-{1. A number between 1 and 7 (such as the 1 in South's 1@C bid).}^-
|
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


cs|2|at|^^^-{2. Any one of the 4 suits (@S, @H, @D, or @C) ^*Ior^*N notrump (such as the @C in South's 1@C bid).}
|
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|bt||n#|5|cs|2|at|So each bid consists of a number between 1 and 7 and either one of the 4 suits or notrump. In bridge literature, NT is frequently used as an abbreviation for notrump when bidding is discussed. The number part of a bid is known as its level and the suit (or notrump) part of a bid is known as its strain. Since there are 7 possible levels that a bid can have and 5 possible strains, there are 35 possible bids in total.

|
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


at|^I     {1@C}|cs|1|at|     {1@D}     {1@H}     {1@S}     {1NT}        

^I     {2@C}     {2@D}     {2@H}     {2@S}     {2NT}        

^I     {3@C}     {3@D}     {3@H}     {3@S}     {3NT}

^I     {4@C}     {4@D}     {4@H}     {4@S}     {4NT}

^I     {5@C}     {5@D}     {5@H}     {5@S}     {5NT}
   
^I     {6@C}     {6@D}     {6@H}     {6@S}     {6NT}

^I     {7@C}     {7@D}     {7@H}     {7@S}     {7NT}

You can see 1@C, South's choice of opening bid in the deal we just saw, at the top left corner of this table. 1 is the level and clubs is the strain of a 1@C bid.|
