 35 of the legal bids in bridge:|
pg| ***** 21 ***** |


ht|S|n#|3|cs|4|at|^-{At a player's turn to bid he can either pass or select one of the 35 bids listed above.
There are a couple of other possibilities in the bidding that will be considered later.}|
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|ht|b|cs|1|at|^-{Bidding is a ^*Iconversation^*N among the 4 players. The purpose of the conversation
is to decide the declarer, his goal, and which suit (if any) will be the trump suit.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


at|The ^*Ilanguage^*N that is used for the bidding conversation does not contain very many words. We have learned almost all of these words already:

|ht|h|cs|3|at|^B { 1 }    { 2 }    { 3 }    { 4 }    { 5 }    { 6 }    { 7 }

|cs|2|at|^B  { @C }   { @D }   { @H }   { @S }   {Notrump} 

|cs|4|at|^E  { Pass }|
pg| ***** 24 ***** |


ht|h|at|^MThere are only 2 other words that are permitted in
^Mthe language of bidding. We will learn about how
^Mthese 2 words are used much later in this program:

|cs|4|at|^P{Double}  ^U{Redouble}

|
pg| ***** 25 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{The bidding continues in a clockwise rotation until ^*I3 consecutive passes^*N are made.
The declarer, his goal, and trump suit (if any) are determined from the last bid made.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 26 ***** |


at|So the bidding can go around the table several times, but it will eventually end when 3 consecutive players choose to pass. The last bid is then used to determine the declarer, goal, and trump suit (or notrump). Here's how:

|
pg| ***** 27 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{1. The trump suit (or notrump) is determined by the strain of the last bid.}

|
pg| ***** 28 ***** |


cs|2|at|{2. Declarer's goal is determined by adding 6 to the level of the last bid.}

|
pg| ***** 29 ***** |


cs|4|at|{3. The declarer is either the player that made the last bid or his partner (more on this soon).}

|
pg| ***** 30 ***** |


st||
nt|^z@3^b@2
Let's review how the principles we have learned about bidding so far might apply to this deal. Remember that South was the dealer, giving him the right to make the first bid. South chose to open the bidding with 1@C. West's turn came next and he chose to pass. It is now North's turn to bid.|
pg| ***** 31 ***** |


mb|p|
nt|^z@3^b@2
Suppose that North also chooses to pass, making it East's turn to bid. As you will learn, it would be a poor idea to pass South's 1@C opening bid with the actual North hand, but right now we are just learning the ^*Imechanics^*N of bidding - not the ^*Istrategy^*N. Don't worry if you know something about bidding already and disagree with any of the bids or passes in the first few examples.

|
pg| ***** 32 ***** |


mb|p|
nt|^z@3^b@2
Suppose that East also passes. 3 consecutive players (West, North, and East) have now passed. That means that the bidding is over. 1@C is the last bid. |
pg| ***** 33 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|2|at|
Here's how the trump suit and goal are determined by the last bid of 1@C:
^^^-{The trump suit is determined by the strain of the last bid - the trump suit is clubs.}
|cs|4|n#|9|at|{The goal is determined by adding 6 to the level of the last bid - the goal is 7 (6+1) tricks.}
|
pg| ***** 34 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
The declarer is either the player that made the last bid (South) or his partner (North). Here is how this vital issue is resolved:|
pg| ***** 35 ***** |


cs|1|at|^^^-{The first member of the partnership to make a bid with the strain of the contract
becomes declarer. South is the only player to have bid at all - he will be declarer.}
|
pg| ***** 36 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
So South will be the declarer. His goal is to win 7 tricks (with North's help, of course). The deal will be played with clubs as the trump suit.|
pg| ***** 37 ***** |


cs|2|at|^^^^^-{Bridge players use the word contract to describe the declarer, his goal, and the
trump suit (if any). On this deal we would say, "The contract is 1@C by South."}
|
pg| ***** 38 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
The notion of the contract is so central to the game of bridge that it is actually part of the game's proper name. That's right, the game you are learning is really called contract bridge, but nowadays most people simply use ^*Ibridge^*N. The name contract bridge appears in the American Contract Bridge League, the organization that produced this program.|
pg| ***** 39 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|4|at|^^ {Historical note:} |cs|1|at|    { ^FContract bridge was born in 1925 when Harold Vanderbilt defined the rules 
^Fand scoring system that are currently in use. Auction bridge, another form of 
^Fthe game, was very popular before Vanderbilt developed ^*Bcontract bridge^*C. 
^FNowadays contract bridge is played almost exclusively.}|
pg| ***** 40 ***** |


pc|dj|
nt|^z@3^b@2
You can see that the contract, 1@C by South, is displayed in the lower right corner of the deal above. It is easy to see the trump suit and the declarer from this. Remember to add 6 to the level of the contract in order to know what the goal is (it is 7 tricks for North-South on this deal).|
pg| ***** 41 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|4|at|
You may think that it is a bit obscure to always add 6 to the level of the contract in order to know what the goal is. There is a good reason for this:
^^^-{The goal always represents a ^*Imajority^*N (7 or more) of the 13 total tricks. 1 is the
lowest level the contract can have. Add 6 to get 7 - the lowest majority of 13.}
|
