up||ub||ub||
nt|^z@3^b@2
Let's back up a little in the bidding to make sure you understand an important point that was made earlier. We have taken back the last 2 passes and, again, it is North's turn to bid.|
pg| ***** 43 ***** |


mb|2c|an|A raise|
nt|^z@3^b@2
Suppose that North chooses to bid 2@C instead of passing. Again, this would be a poor choice of bids, but don't worry about that now. Since North's partner has already bid 1@C and since North's 2@C raises the level with clubs as trump, we use the word raise to describe this type of bid.|
pg| ***** 44 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
Why would North ever want to raise the level of the bidding? After all, we know that a 1@C contract requires only 7 tricks, but a 2@C contract requires 8 tricks - a more ambitious goal.|
pg| ***** 45 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|2|ht|c|at|^^^-{If a partnership succeeds in taking enough tricks to satisfy the contract they will win
points. Some contracts at the higher levels reward success with lots of bonus points.}^-
|
pg| ***** 46 ***** |


cs|1|at|^^^-{Partnerships will frequently attempt ambitious contracts in order to gain bonus points.
Players raise the bidding level so that they will have a chance to win these bonus points.}

|
pg| ***** 47 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|ht|c|cs|4|at|^^^-{^*UWarning:^*N Trying for these bonus points is not free. If the declarer fails to win enough
tricks for his contract, it is the defenders' partnership that will score points on the deal.}
|
