cs|1|at|^^^^^-{South is the declarer as he was the ^*Ifirst^*N member of the partnership to bid the trump suit.}
|
pg| ***** 51 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
The mechanics of bidding are quite simple and you have been introduced to most of these already. The hard part of bidding is learning when you should pass and what bid you should make, if instead, you choose to bid.|
PG| ***** 52 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
For example, North's 2@C is not a very good choice of bids with his hand. We will learn why shortly.|
pg| ***** 53 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|ub||ub||ub||ub||at|
We have backed up again to North's first turn to bid. What you are about to see is a recommended bidding sequence for this deal. Do not expect to understand ^*Iwhy^*N the bids and passes you are about to see are recommended. You will understand soon.|
pg| ***** 54 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|mb|1h|an|
The response|mb|p|mb|1s|an|Opener's rebid|mb|p|mb|4s|an|Responder's rebid|mb|p|mb|p|mb|p|
nt|^z@3^b@2
In the bidding sequence above, East and West have passed throughout, but North and South have both been busy - they have each made 2 bids. |
