cs|2|at|^-{1. Should the declarer be from our partnership or should we be defenders on this deal?}

|
pg| ***** 183 ***** |


cs|4|at|{2. If the declarer is from our partnership, what should the level of the contract be?}

|
pg| ***** 184 ***** |


cs|1|at|{3. If the declarer is from our partnership, what should the strain of the contract be?}
^-
|
pg| ***** 185 ***** |


at|The first and second questions are harder to answer than the third one. That is due to the fact that the selection of the best strain does not involve any more than the partnership figuring out in which of the 4 suits they were dealt the most combined cards. Answering the first 2 questions involves figuring out the trick-winning strength of the partnership's hands. This is much harder to quantify than the number of combined cards that the partnership was dealt in various suits.|
pg| ***** 186 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|Here again are the 3 main partnership objectives for the bidding:

|cs|2|at|^-{1. Should the declarer be from our partnership or should we be defenders on this deal?}

|cs|4|at|{2. If the declarer is from our partnership, what should the level of the contract be?}

|cs|1|at|{3. If the declarer is from our partnership, what should the strain of the contract be?}
^-
We have already made some good progress in how the partnership should go about answering the third question.

|
pg| ***** 187 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{First the partnership tries to figure out in which of the 4 suits they were dealt the ^*Imost^*N
^*Icombined cards^*N. They also try to figure out how many cards are in their longest fit.}

|
pg| ***** 188 ***** |


cs|2|at|{If the longest fit is less than 8-cards, the deal usually belongs in notrump.}

|
pg| ***** 189 ***** |


cs|4|at|{If the longest fit is 8-cards or more, that suit should usually be the trump suit.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 190 ***** |


cs|1|at|We have already seen one exception to the last of these guidelines:
^-
{5@D and 5@C are usually contracts to avoid even if an 8-card (or longer) minor suit fit exists.
3NT is often an easier contract in this case and offers the same game bonus as 5@D and 5@C.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 191 ***** |


at|The above guidelines will do a pretty good job with respect to selecting the best strain for the contract. Now let's investigate what considerations apply to selecting the appropriate level.|
pg| ***** 192 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|To answer these questions effectively:
|cs|2|n#|8|at|^-{1. Should the declarer be from our partnership or should we be defenders on this deal?}

|cs|4|at|{2. If the declarer is from our partnership, what should the level of the contract be?}
^-
The partnership must judge how many tricks they are likely to win in their best strain.

|
pg| ***** 193 ***** |


at|It is easy to look at a bridge hand and say, "I have 5 spades." It is not so easy to look at a bridge hand and say, "I can win 9 tricks with spades as trump with the help of my partner."

|cs|1|at|^-{Judging the number of tricks the partnership can win is not an exact science.
The best we can do is to think about what features of a hand contribute to winning tricks.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 194 ***** |


at|Fortunately, we have already learned quite a bit about how to win tricks. We know:

|cs|3|at|^-{An Ace will always win a trick (unless it is ruffed).}

|
pg| ***** 195 ***** |


cs|2|at|{A King will often win a trick (if the partnership also holds the Ace in that suit,
or by finessing against the Ace, or by promotion if the Queen is also present).}

|
pg| ***** 196 ***** |


cs|4|at|{Queens and Jacks win tricks less frequently, but still represent valuable assets.
Strong middle cards (10s and 9s) will also come into play in many card combinations.}

|
pg| ***** 197 ***** |


cs|1|at|{In general, the higher a card the more likely it is to win a trick.}

|
pg| ***** 198 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
It is no big surprise that high cards tend to win tricks. We have also seen:

|cs|1|at|^-{Having several high cards ^*Iconcentrated^*N in the same suit is a good thing, especially in long
suits. High cards in short suits (especially singletons) often have little trick-winning value.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 199 ***** |


at|High cards are not the only features of a bridge hand that contribute to winning tricks.

|cs|3|at|^-{Small cards in long suits often win tricks through suit establishment.
Having a long suit (or more than one) will often be worth several extra tricks.}

|
pg| ***** 200 ***** |


cs|2|at|{Short suits can also be a valuable asset, but only if a good trump fit is present. Short suits 
can win extra tricks with ruffs and they can stop the defenders from running their long suits.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 201 ***** |


at|So high cards win tricks, low cards in long suits win tricks, and short suits can win tricks (as long an adequate trump fit is present).

We know how to win tricks. What we need now is a way to ^*Imeasure^*N a bridge hand in terms of how many tricks it is likely to win. Ideally we would like to come up with a ^*Iformula^*N for evaluating a hand's trick-winning potential. Such a formula should take into account all of the factors that we have seen that contribute to winning tricks.

|
pg| ***** 202 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{^*UGood news!!!^*N There is such a formula and it is very easy to learn!
The formula is called the 4-3-2-1 point count.}
|
pg| ***** 203 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|4|at|
 {Historical note:} |cs|1|at|^F{Charles Goren, arguably the most famous bridge player ever, standardized
^Fand popularized the 4-3-2-1 point count in the late 1940s. Goren's system
^Fmade it much easier for average bridge players to learn bidding and to bid
^Faccurately. Contract bridge quickly became the most popular card game in the
^Fworld, largely as a result of Goren's contribution.} 

|
pg| ***** 204 ***** |


at|The 4-3-2-1 point count is a ^*Iformula^*N for estimating a hand's trick-winning potential. Every 13-card bridge hand is assigned a specific number of points using this formula. The more points a hand contains the more tricks that hand is likely to win. Here's how it works:

|
pg| ***** 205 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{Count ^*I4 points^*N for every ^*IAce^*N in your hand.}

|
pg| ***** 206 ***** |


cs|2|at|{Count ^*I3 points^*N for every ^*IKing^*N in your hand.}

|
pg| ***** 207 ***** |


cs|4|at|{Count ^*I2 points^*N for every ^*IQueen^*N in your hand.}

|
pg| ***** 208 ***** |


cs|1|at|{Count ^*I1 point^*N for every ^*IJack^*N in your hand.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 209 ***** |


at|The total you come up with is known as the high card point (or HCP) value of your hand.

|
pg| ***** 210 ***** |


at|It is easy to see why Goren called his formula the 4-3-2-1 point count and why this formula is so easy to remember and to use. Take a moment and make sure you remember:

|cs|3|at|^-{Aces are worth 4 HCP, Kings 3, Queens 2, and Jacks 1.}
|
pg| ***** 211 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
Try counting the high card points for this hand using the 4-3-2-1 scale:

|cs|3|at|^-{|ih|psak5432hkq2d2ckqj|at|}

|
pg| ***** 212 ***** |


cs|2|at|{The hand contains 1 Ace, the @SA. Each Ace is worth 4 HCP.
The hand contains 4 HCP in Aces.}

|
pg| ***** 213 ***** |


cs|4|at|{The hand contains 3 Kings, the @SK, @HK, and @CK. Each King is worth 3 HCP.
The hand contains 9 HCP in Kings.}

|
pg| ***** 214 ***** |


cs|1|at|{The hand contains 2 Queens, the @HQ and the @CQ. Each Queen is worth 2 HCP.
The hand contains 4 HCP in Queens.}

|
pg| ***** 215 ***** |


cs|3|at|{The hand contains 1 Jack, the @CJ. Each Jack is worth 1 HCP.
The hand contains 1 HCP in Jacks.}


|
pg| ***** 216 ***** |


cs|2|at|{There are 4 HCP in Aces, 9 HCP in Kings, 4 HCP in Queens, and 1 HCP in Jacks.
The grand total is 18. The above hand contains 18 high card points.}
|
pg| ***** 217 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
See, it was not very difficult to figure out that this hand contains 18 HCP:

|cs|3|at|^-{|ih|psak5432hkq2d2ckqj|at|}
^-
In fact, this was a relatively difficult hand for the purposes of counting points (because this hand contains several cards that count towards the total).

|
pg| ***** 218 ***** |


at|With most hands, counting high card points is much easier. For example:

^-{|ih|psqj6h6543da543c32|at|}
^-
|
pg| ***** 219 ***** |


at|This hand contains only 3 cards that count for any high card points, the @DA (4 HCP), the @SQ (2 HCP), and the @SJ (1 HCP). There are 7 HCP in total in this hand.

|
pg| ***** 220 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|3|n#|5|at|Here again are the 2 hands that we just saw:

^D{|ih|psak5432hkq2d2ckqj|at|} |n#|t|at|^P{|ih|psqj6h6543da543c32|at|} 
|n^|9|cs|2|at|^d{18 high card points} ^p {7 high card points}


It is a good sign that the first hand (with 18 HCP) obviously rates to win several more tricks than the second hand (with only 7 HCP). It appears that Charles Goren was on to something very useful with the 4-3-2-1 point count!

|
pg| ***** 221 ***** |


at|OK, so we know how to count our high card points and that the more points a hand has the more tricks it is likely to win. How does this help us in deciding what we should bid and how does it help the partnership figure out what the best contract rates to be?

Goren's contribution to bidding theory went far beyond the standardization of the 4-3-2-1 point count. Goren also figured out the number of high card points between the partnership's hands that rate to be enough for various contracts to succeed.

|
pg| ***** 222 ***** |


ht|S|cs|4|at|^-{The 4-3-2-1 point count is more than just a way to measure a hand's trick-winning
potential. It is also a guide to help the partnership find the right level for their contract.}
|
pg| ***** 223 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|Here is an example of how the 4-3-2-1 point count can help the partnership judge an appropriate level for the contract:
|n#|8|cs|2|at|^-{Goren showed that 25 points between the 2 hands is usually enough to
make either 3NT, 4@S, or 4@H (all game contracts) a reasonable proposition.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 224 ***** |


at|Let's look at the 2 hands we just saw and imagine that North was dealt the 7 HCP hand and that his partner, South, was dealt the 18 HCP hand:

|cs|3|at|^-{|ih|psqj6h6543da543c32|at|}
^^
{|ih|psak5432hkq2d2ckqj|at|}
^-
|
pg| ***** 225 ***** |


at|There are 25 HCP between the 2 hands - enough to suggest that either 3NT, 4@S, or 4@H rates to be a good contract. Since the partnership has a 9-card fit in spades, spades should be selected as the strain of the contract. 4@S rates to be the best contract with these cards.|
pg| ***** 226 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|It turns out that the 4-3-2-1 point count is very accurate in suggesting the 4@S should be the best contract with these 2 hands:
|ht|c|n#|3|cs|3|at|^-{|ih|psqj6h6543da543c32|at|}
^^
{|ih|psak5432hkq2d2ckqj|at|}
^-
To see this, count South's losers. North's @SQ and @SJ fill in South's spade suit such that there will be no losers in the trump suit. The @HA and @CA will surely win tricks for the defenders and they may come to a second heart trick as well. Still, that is only 3 losers at the most. North-South should be able to win at least the 10 tricks that 4@S demands. 

|
pg| ***** 227 ***** |


at|Now imagine that North is able to give South this message in the bidding: "Partner, I have 7 HCP and 3 cards in spades. Please use this information to pick a contract!"

|
pg| ***** 228 ***** |


at|South would know to pick a contract of 4@S - he would know that the 2 hands contained enough HCP (25 or more) and enough spades (8 or more) to make 4@S into a good bet.|
pg| ***** 229 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|Before we talk about how North-South can describe their hands to one another in the bidding (so that one of them is able to pick the best contract) there is an ^*Iextremely important^*N lesson about the 4-3-2-1 point count that you must learn.

|
pg| ***** 230 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{The 4-3-2-1 point count generally works very well, but it does not come with any guarantees.
Sometimes the contract suggested by the 4-3-2-1 point count will not be a success.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 231 ***** |


ht|i|cs|3|at|^B{|ih|psqj6h6543da543c32|at|}
^^
^B{|ih|psak5432hkq2d2ckqj|at|}

|ht|i|n#|5|at|^KWith the hands we have been looking at 4@S (a contract
^Kthat 4-3-2-1 suggests) could fail. Perhaps one defender
^Kwas dealt a singleton heart and the other defender was
^Kdealt a singleton club. The defenders will be able to win
^Kthe first several tricks on a crossruff, defeating 4@S.


^KThat does not mean 4-3-2-1 was wrong. 4@S is a very 
^Kgood contract - it will only be defeated if North-South are
^Kextremely unlucky. Nevertheless, at times 4-3-2-1 will
