pg| ***** 232 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|Before we talk about how North-South can describe their hands to one another in the bidding (so that one of them is able to pick the best contract) there is an ^*Iextremely important^*N lesson about the 4-3-2-1 point count that you must learn.
^^|

cs|2|at|^-{The 4-3-2-1 point count generally works very well, but it does not come with any guarantees.
Sometimes the contract suggested by the 4-3-2-1 point count will not be a success.}
^-^^|

ht|i|cs|3|at|^B{|ih|psqj6h6543dkj43c32|at|}
^^
^B{|ih|psak5432hkq2d2ckqj|at|}

|ht|i|n#|5|at|^KWith the hands we have been looking at 4@S (a contract
^Kthat 4-3-2-1 suggests) could fail. Perhaps one defender
^Kwas dealt a singleton heart and the other defender was
^Kdealt a singleton club. The defenders will be able to win
^Kthe first several tricks on a crossruff, defeating 4@S.


^KThat does not mean 4-3-2-1 was wrong. 4@S is a very 
^Kgood contract - it will only be defeated if North-South are
^Kextremely unlucky. Nevertheless, at times 4-3-2-1 will
^Ksteer the partnership into a poor contract.
|

ht|t|at|The North hand now has the @DK and @DJ instead of the @DA. North still has 7 HCP and there are still 25 HCP between the 2 hands. 4@S is not such a great contract anymore - South now has a certain loser in diamonds. 4@S still might succeed, but North-South will need considerably more luck now that North has the @DKJ intead of the @DA.|
pg| ***** 233 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|While high card points are a reasonable measure of a hand's trick-winning potential, they do not tell the whole story. Consider the first hand that we looked at for point-counting purposes:
|ht|d|cs|3|at|^-{|ih|psak5432hkq2d2ckqj|at|}
^-
This hand has 18 HCP, but high cards are not the only reason that this hand is so strong. 

|
pg| ***** 234 ***** |


at|The 6-card spade suit is a major asset. If spades are trump this hand will likely win several tricks with small cards in spades. Even at notrump or with another suit as trump, there is a good chance that several small spades will win tricks via suit establishment. The 4-3-2-1 point count does not factor in the trick-winning power of a long suit.

|
pg| ***** 235 ***** |


at|There is a good solution to this problem that leads to more accurate hand evaluation:
|n#|8|cs|2|at|^-{Add 1 point if a hand contains a 5-card suit and 1 point for each additional card
in the long suit. These points are called long suit points or distribution points.}
^-
|ht|R|n#|8|at|The hand above contains 2 long suit points courtesy of the 6-card spade suit. By adding the high card points (18) and the long suit points (2), we arrive at the total points (20). Total points are a much more accurate reflection of a hand's value than high card points alone.
|
pg| ***** 236 ***** |


ht|U|n#|6|cs|4|at|^-{Total points = High card points + Long suit points}
|
pg| ***** 237 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
Try figuring out the total points for this hand with 2 long suits:

|cs|3|at|^-{|ih|pss2ha5432c2dkq5432|at|}
^-
|
pg| ***** 238 ***** |


at|There are 9 high card points (4 for the @HA, 3 for the @DK, and 2 for the @DQ). Both hearts and diamonds contribute long suit points to this hand. The 5-card heart suit is worth 1 long suit point and the 6-card diamond suit is worth 2 long suit points. That makes 3 long suit points between hearts and diamonds. 9 high card points plus 3 long suit points equals 12 total points.

|
pg| ***** 239 ***** |


at|We have seen several deals in which short suits are an asset as well. In particular, if the deal contains a trump suit, a short side suit in the dummy will often produce extra tricks by allowing declarer to ruff his losers. There are times when points should be added for short suits, but we will cover those situations in the next chapter.

|
pg| ***** 240 ***** |


cs|4|at| {Historical note:} |cs|1|at|^F{Goren orginally counted points for short suits (instead of long suits) to
^Fcalculate the total points of a hand. Goren counted 1 short suit point for
^Feach doubleton, 2 for each singleton, and 3 for each void. Over the years it
^Fbecame apparent that long suit points were more accurate, as they provided 
^Fa more realistic assessment of where a hand's true trick source resides.}
|
pg| ***** 241 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
We now know how to figure out how many total points a hand contains:

|cs|4|at|^-{Total points = High card points + Long suit points}
^-
|
pg| ***** 242 ***** |


at|We also know which contracts award bonus points to a successful declarer and we have some good guidelines for selecting the best strain for the contract. In an prior example we saw:

|cs|1|at|^-{25 total points between the 2 hands is usually enough to make
either 3NT, 4@S, or 4@H (all game contracts) a reasonable proposition.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 243 ***** |


at|Here are some more useful guidelines for selecting the best contract:

|cs|2|at|^-{Presuming an adequate minor suit fit exists, it takes 29 total points between 
the 2 hands before either 5@D or 5@C (11 trick game contracts) rate to be reasonable.}

|cs|3|at|{33 total points between the 2 hands is usually enough for a small slam (12 tricks).}

|cs|4|at|{37 total points between the 2 hands is usually enough for a grand slam (13 tricks).}
^-
|
pg| ***** 244 ***** |


cs|1|at|Here is a general rule to make it easier to remember these numbers:

^-{4@S and 4@H are 10-trick contracts that require 25 total points between the 2 hands.
Add 4 total points (the equivalent of an Ace) for each extra trick that a contract demands.}
|
pg| ***** 245 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|
