%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
qx|bid,wide Introduction to our bidding system|
nt|^z@3^b@2|fp|t|cs|1|at|
^-{  Introduction to our bidding system  }
^-|fp||at|
We now have good set of rules for choosing the level and strain of the contract. If a player is able to tell his partner how many total points his hand contains and how many cards he was dealt in various suits, the partner can use this information to select a good contract. That's exactly what the bidding is all about. This task is easier said than done. Here is the main reason:|
pg| ***** 246 ***** |


cs|1|at|

^-{You cannot simply say to your partner, "I have 6 spades and 20 total points." The very
limited language of the bidding must be used to tell your partner about your hand.}
^-
|cs|2|at|It is possible for a partnership to communicate effectively in the bidding, even with the small number of words that the language of bidding contains. In order for the 2 partners to understand each other they must ^*Iagree on the meanings^*N of various bids. For example, the partnership may choose to make some rules like this:

|
pg| ***** 247 ***** |


at|^-{A 1@S opening bid promises 5 or more cards in spades and between 13 and 21 total points.}
^-
|at|Imagine that you and your partner agreed to make this rule. Every time that you opened the bidding with 1@S your partner would know immediately quite a bit about your hand. Your subsequent bids could be used to tell your partner more about your hand (like narrowing the 13-21 total point range or describing your lengths in other suits).

At some point your partner will hopefully have enough information about your hand to select the best contract for the partnership.|
pg| ***** 248 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|2|at|
Some big questions remain. How do we come up with rules like the following?

^-{A 1@S opening bid promises 5 or more cards in spades and between 13 and 21 total points.}
^-
How do we know the rules we come up with are good ones? How can we reasonably expect a new partner to be able to learn our preferred rules without having to study them extensively?

|
pg| ***** 249 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{^*UGreat news!!!^*N We don't have to worry about the answers to any of these questions.
There is a ^*Istandard^*N set of rules that describe the ^*Imeanings^*N of various bids.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 250 ***** |


at|It will come as no surprise that it was Charles Goren who developed the initial set of bidding rules for the 4-3-2-1 point count. Goren used the name Standard American for his bidding system (a bidding system is a set of several rules like the one above).

Standard American was so easy to learn and so effective that it quickly lived up to its name, becoming the ^*Istandard^*N bidding system in America as well as several other parts of the world. Standard American made it possible for 2 strangers to sit down at a bridge table as partners and understand each other's bids.

Over the years various bridge theorists have experimented with changing the definitions of some of the bids in Standard American. Some of these changes worked so well that they gradually caught on. Today's Standard American is different in some ways from the bidding system that Goren originally defined.|
pg| ***** 251 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|Most of the remainder of this program will be devoted to teaching you a bidding system that is best thought of as a modernized version of Goren's teachings. Once you learn this bidding system you will be able to play bridge with just about anyone as your partner. The bidding system you will learn doesn't really have an official name, but we will call it:

|cs|1|at|^-{Modern Standard American with 5-Card Majors}
^-
|
pg| ***** 252 ***** |


at|You have just learned where the "Modern Standard American" part of this name comes from. The "5-Card Majors" part comes from one of the most important rules in this bidding system:

|cs|4|at|^-{A 1@H or 1@S opening bid promises ^*Iat least 5 cards^*N in the suit named.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 253 ***** |


at|This is one of the biggest differences between our bidding system and Goren's original Standard American. Goren's system allowed for major suit opening bids to be made on 4-card (or longer) suits. The modern theory is that 5-card majors is both easier to learn and more effective than Goren's system of 4-card majors.

|
pg| ***** 254 ***** |


at|Here is another rule that will be part of our bidding system:

|cs|2|at|^-{A 1@C, 1@D, 1@H, or 1@S opening bid promises ^*Iat least 13^*N total points.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 255 ***** |


at|The average bridge hand contains 10 HCP - 1 Ace, 1 King, 1 Queen, and 1 Jack (there are 4 of each of these cards and 4 players so each player on average will be dealt 1 of each of these cards). It makes good sense that an opening bid should describe an above-average hand. With an average hand, it makes sense to pass as you don't really have anything to say.|
pg| ***** 256 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
Here again are the 2 bidding ^*Irules^*N that we have learned so far:

|cs|4|at|^-{A 1@H or 1@S opening bid promises ^*Iat least 5 cards^*N in the suit named.}

|cs|2|at|{A 1@C, 1@D, 1@H, or 1@S opening bid promises ^*Iat least 13^*N total points.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 257 ***** |


at|You are going to learn several rules like these in the lessons that follow. First there is something ^*Ivery important^*N that you should know about the nature of such rules:

|cs|1|at|^-{The above "rules" are not rules in the same sense as, "You must follow suit if you can."
A player is always free to make ^*Iany legal bid^*N, regardless of his partnership's bidding ^*Irules^*N.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 258 ***** |


at|That means you are allowed to open the bidding with less than 13 total points, you can pass with 13 or more total points, and you are welcome to open the bidding 1@H or 1@S with fewer than 5 cards if you feel like it. You will be breaking your partnership's rules, but you will not be breaking the rules of the game of bridge.

This does not suggest that it is a good idea to depart from the bidding system you and your partner use. In fact, it is generally a very bad idea - your partner will be misled as to the nature of your hand and he may choose a poor contract as a result.

|
pg| ***** 259 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{It is almost always correct to bid according to the partnership's rules. You are always
allowed to use your judgement, however, and make a non-system bid if you think it is wise.}
|
pg| ***** 260 ***** |


