We now have a complete set of rules for deciding which suit to open at the 1-level. The next question we will explore is when a player should open the bidding with 1NT.

We have studied the play of the cards on many deals, both at notrump and when there is a trump suit. Recall that notrump tended to work well when the declarer's hand contained:

|
pg| ***** 270 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{1. Lots of high cards - both for winning tricks and for stopping the defenders' long suits.}

|
pg| ***** 271 ***** |


cs|2|at|{2. No voids or singletons - very short suits must be stopped with ruffs (thus a trump suit).}
^-
|
pg| ***** 272 ***** |


cs|3|at|Our definition of a 1NT opening bid reflects both these conditions:

^-{A 1NT opening bid promises between 15 and 17 HCP (not total points) in a balanced
hand. A balanced hand contains no voids or singletons and at most 1 doubleton.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 273 ***** |


at|There are 10 (4+3+2+1) HCP in each of the 4 suits, therefore 40 HCP in the deck. These 40 HCP rate to be divided evenly among the 4 players, making 10 HCP an average hand.

The 15-17 HCP range for a 1NT opening bid represents a hand that is worth more than an Ace (4 points) above average. That is enough to satisfy the first indication that a notrump contract might be best - lots of high cards. Since a balanced hand is required for a 1NT opening bid, the second indication that notrump might be best is also satisfied by our definition.

|
pg| ***** 274 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|So a 1NT opening bid promises 15-17 HCP and a balanced hand. There is one more thing you should know about 1NT openings before we look at some example hands:

|cs|1|at|^-{Our rule about when to open the bidding with 1NT takes priority over all of our other rules.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 275 ***** |


