Notice how our definition of a 1NT opening bid has a relatively ^*Inarrow^*N HCP range:

|cs|1|at|^-{A 1NT opening bid promises between 15 and 17 HCP and a balanced hand.}
^-
|at|The difference between a minimum 1NT opening bid (15 HCP) and a maximum 1NT opening bid (17 HCP) is only 2 HCP. The fact that 1NT limits the opener's hand to such a narrow range is a very powerful concept. The partner of a 1NT opener will know immediately whether the best contract is likely to be a partial, game, small slam, or grand slam.

|
pg| ***** 278 ***** |


at|For example, imagine that your partner 
opens the bidding with 1NT. Your hand is:|
ht|m|cs|3|at|^N{|ih|psAQ87hk964dj32ct8|at|}

|
pg| ***** 279 ***** |


ht|q|at|You have 10 HCP and you know your
partner has at least 15 HCP.
 
There must be at least 25 HCP between the 2 hands - enough for either 3NT, 4@S, or 4@H to be a reasonable contract. You know the partnership belongs in a game contract and you can use the rest of the bidding to discover in which strain game rates to be best (you will learn how soon).

|
pg| ***** 280 ***** |


at|Furthermore, since partner's 1NT has an upper limit of 17 HCP you also know immediately that a slam contract is impossible. The partnership has at most 27 points between the 2 hands - not even close to the 33 combined points that are usually required for a small slam.|
pg| ***** 281 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|4|at|
^-{One of the main goals in bidding is to limit the strength of your hand as ^*Inarrowly as possible^*N.
Your partner will then be able to judge whether a partial, game, or slam contract is best.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 282 ***** |


at|The 1NT opening bid does a great job of immediately limiting opener's hand, placing the responder in an excellent position to judge the best level of the contract. The point range we have been using for 1@C, 1@D, 1@H, and 1@S opening bids is not as narrowly defined. In fact, we do not even have an upper limit on the strength of these bids:

|cs|1|at|^-{Opening bids of 1@C, 1@D, 1@H, and 1@S promise 13 or more total points.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 283 ***** |


at|Imagine that you are dealt the same hand and your partner opens 1@D intead of 1NT:

|cs|3|at|^-{|ih|psAQ87hk964dj32ct8|at|}
^-
|
pg| ***** 284 ***** |


ht|Q|at|If your partner has a minimum hand with 13 total points, your 10 points mean that a partial rates to be best - 23 combined total points are less than the 25 total points that a game contract requires. If partner is a little stronger, however, a game contract should be reached. If partner is very strong, a small slam or even grand slam could be best.

|
pg| ***** 285 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{As 1@D is not narrowly limited, the best level of the contract is unknown.}
|
pg| ***** 286 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|It is, therefore, a good idea to place an upper limit on the strength of opening bids of 1 of a suit. It would be nice if we could make the maximum for such bids to be around 15 total points. That would narrow the range of 1-level suit openings to 13-15 total points - the same 2 point difference between a minimum and maximum 1NT opening bid.

It turns out that placing such a narrow range on opening bids of 1 of a suit causes more problems than it solves. Our effective range for these bids will be quite wide, but at least they will now have an upper limit:

|
pg| ***** 287 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{Opening bids of 1@C, 1@D, 1@H, and 1@S promise between 13 and 21 total points.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 288 ***** |


at|So now when you hold this hand and partner opens the bidding with 1@D:

|cs|3|at|^-{|ih|psAQ87hk964dj32ct8|at|}
^-
You won't know for sure what the level of the contract should be, but you will know that it must be either a partial or a game contract. Even if partner has a maximum hand with 21 total points, the 33 total points required for a small slam will not be present. As you will learn, in most cases opener can use his rebid to place a much more narrow limit on the number of total points in his hand.|
