nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|1|at|
^-{Opening the bidding with very strong hands}
^-
You are probably wondering what you are supposed to do as the opening bidder if you are fortunate enough to be dealt 22 or more total points. You can't open these hands with 1 of a suit because of our new and improved rule for these bids:

|cs|1|at|^-{Opening bids of 1@C, 1@D, 1@H, and 1@S promise between 13 and 21 total points.}
^-
If you opened a 22 point (or stronger) hand at the 1-level your partner would be misled into thinking that you had a weaker hand (21 points at the most). As such your partner could easily place the contract at too low a level. We will use 2 different opening bids to describe very strong hands:

|
pg| ***** 332 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{1. A 3NT opening bid promises between 25 and 27 HCP and a balanced hand.}

|cs|2|at|{2. A 2@C opening bid is used for all other hands with 22 or more total points.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 333 ***** |


at|The first of these rules is intuitively very sensible. We have already learned that 25 total points are usually sufficient to make 3NT (or 4@S or 4@H) a reasonable contract. By opening the bidding with 3NT you are giving this message: "Partner, I have enough points in my own hand to make 3NT a reasonable contract even if your hand contains no points at all!"

The balanced hand requirement for a 3NT opening also makes sense - we have already seen how such hands are suitable for notrump play.|
pg| ***** 334 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|2|at|
Our second rule for opening the bidding with very strong hands is not very intuitive at all:

^-{A 2@C opening bid is used for all hands with 22 or more total points that
are unsuitable for a 3NT opening bid (a balanced hand with 25-27 HCP).}
^-
|
pg| ***** 335 ***** |


cs|3|at|Suppose, for example, that you are dealt this beautiful hand:

^-{|ih|psakhakqjt83da97c6|at|}
^-
This hand contains 24 total points (21 HCP and 3 long suit points for the 7-card heart suit). According to the above rule, the correct opening bid with this hand is 2@C.

|
pg| ***** 336 ***** |


at|How can that be right? What if your partner passes your 2@C opening bid? This hand will almost certainly win 10 tricks with hearts as trump (enough for a game contract of 4@H) without any help from partner. The play is not likely to be very pleasant, however, if clubs are trump (not to mention that 2@C is a partial contract that awards no bonus points to a successful declarer).

|
pg| ***** 337 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{The 2@C opening bid is an example of an artificial forcing bid. The artificial part means
that the 2@C bid says nothing about clubs. The forcing part means that partner cannot pass.}
|
pg| ***** 338 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
We just got our first look at 2 new bridge words, artificial and forcing. These words were used to describe the 2@C opening bid - the bid we will be making on all hands with 22 or more total points that are unsuitable for a 3NT opening bid.

An artificial bid is a bid that says nothing about the strain named and does not suggest a final contract. The opposite of an artificial bid is a natural bid. A natural bid suggests a final contract and says something about the strain that was named.

You may have heard the word convention used to describe these artificial bids. For example, "the 2@C opening bid is my partnership's convention for showing a very strong hand," or "the 2@C opening is a conventional bid."

|
pg| ***** 339 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{A convention is like a ^*Icoded^*N bid that the partnership uses to exchange information.
Thousands of conventions have been devised, but only a few have become widely accepted.}

|
pg| ***** 340 ***** |


cs|1|at|{It is a very important rule of bridge that the ^*Icodes^*N used by conventions are ^*Inot secret^*N.
If your partnership adopts a particular convention, you must inform the opposing partnership.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 341 ***** |


at|Imagine that you are sitting South and open the bidding with 2@C. It is West's turn to bid. He has the right to ask, "What does that bid mean?" The rules of bridge obligate you to tell him, "2@C is an artificial forcing bid showing 22 or more total points."

The same rule applies to natural bids. Suppose you opened 1@H as South. West could ask, "Do you use 5-card majors?" You would have to truthfully answer his question.

|
pg| ***** 342 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|2|at|
^-{Bridge is a very honest game. Any agreements that a partnership makes about
the meanings of various bids must be ^*Idisclosed^*N to the opposing partnership.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 343 ***** |


at|You may be wondering why we are going to open almost all of our very strong hands with 2@C. It wasn't always this way. In Goren's original Standard American, 2@C, 2@D, 2@H, and 2@S opening bids were all used to describe very strong hands. Goren's 2-level suit openings were natural bids - the opening bidder with a very strong hand would bid his longest and strongest suit at the 2-level. This approach became known as strong 2-bids.

Over the years it became apparent that it was quite rare to be dealt a hand strong enough to qualify for a strong 2-bid. The idea of opening 2@C on all such hands was born, freeing up the 2@D, 2@H, and 2@S openings to describe other types of hands (more on this soon). 2@C became an artificial bid - it said nothing about clubs, only that the opening bidder held a very strong hand.

The concept of using 2@C as the only strong 2-level opening bid worked so well in practice that nowadays it is more or less the ^*Istandard^*N among top bridge players in North America. There are still some partnerships that use Goren's strong 2-bids, but their numbers get smaller each year.

|
pg| ***** 344 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{Standard American evolved as new conventions and approaches were developed.
A few of these have withstood the test of time and have become part of the ^*Imodern standard^*N.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 345 ***** |


at|Goren got a lot of things right, but there were some areas of his bidding system that left room for improvement. The decline of strong 2-bids and 4-card majors represent the 2 biggest changes from Goren's Standard American to the accepted ^*Istandard^*N of today.|
pg| ***** 346 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|Not only is our 2@C opening an artificial bid, it is also a forcing bid.

|cs|2|at|^-{When your partner makes a forcing bid you must never pass. 
No matter how weak your hand is you must find some bid to make.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 347 ***** |


at|It is easy to understand why our 2@C opening bid should be defined as forcing. Have another look at the example hand that was given for a 2@C opening bid:

|cs|3|ht|h|at|^g{|ih|psakhakqjt83da97c6|at|}|
pg| ***** 348 ***** |


ht|m|at|Suppose you are dealt the hand on the left and properly open the bidding with 2@C. Suppose further that your partner was dealt the terrible hand on the right with a 6-card club suit.
|ht|h|at|^Q{|ih|ps432h2d432c543287|at|}
|
pg| ***** 349 ***** |


ht|p|at|Your partner's first instinct might be to pass your 2@C opening bid - he certainly would want clubs to be trump and he does not have enough points to suggest a game or slam contract. Passing 2@C would be a serious error. 
A game contract of 4@H is almost certain to succeed with these 2 hands, even though the weak hand will not be able to win any tricks.

|
pg| ***** 350 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{Never pass when your partner opens 2@C! Your partner's hand is likely strong enough to win
enough tricks for a game contract without any help from you. That's why 2@C is a forcing bid.}
|
pg| ***** 351 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|4|at|
^-{It is not a rule of bridge that you must not pass when your partner makes a forcing bid.
Remember that you can always make ^*Iany^*N legal bid or pass whenever you feel like it.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 352 ***** |


at|The reason you should not pass when your partner opens 2@C (or any of the other forcing bids that we will learn about) has nothing to do with the rules of bridge. It is all about trusting your partner and having confidence in the bidding system that you are using.

Whenever your partner makes a forcing bid he is saying:

"Partner, I have not finished describing my hand yet. Even if your hand is very weak I think we may be able to win enough tricks for a game or slam contract. Please respect my judgement and keep the bidding open no matter how horrible your hand is!"

|
pg| ***** 353 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{Trusting and respecting your partner in the bidding is vital to success at bridge.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 354 ***** |


cs|2|at|Here are the 2 main ways you can show trust in and respect toward your partner:

^-{1. Never pass when your partner makes a bid that is forcing in the bidding system.}

|cs|3|at|{2. Make sure that the bids you make accord to the definitions that we have established.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 355 ***** |


at|The rules of bridge do not force you to bid within the guidelines. However, by doing so, you not only make your partner happy, you also increase your chances of finding the best possible contract.|
pg| ***** 356 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|1|n#|5|at|We have already seen:

^-{1. A 1NT opening bid promises between 15 and 17 HCP and a balanced hand.}

|cs|4|at|{2. A 3NT opening bid promises between 25 and 27 HCP and a balanced hand.}
^-
How about a 2NT opening bid?|
pg| ***** 357 ***** |


cs|2|at|^^^^^-{A 2NT opening bid promises between 20 and 21 HCP and a balanced hand.}
^-
It makes sense that the 2NT opening bid also promises a balanced hand and that its HCP range is about halfway between 1NT and 3NT. Notice that the range of a 2NT opening is only 2 HCP in size while 1NT and 3NT openings both have 3 HCP ranges.|
pg| ***** 358 ***** |


