^-{  Preemptive opening bids  }
^-|fp||at|
It is time to have a look at opening bids of 2@D, 2@H, and 2@S as well as suit opening bids at the 3-level and higher. It was mentioned earlier that Goren used all opening bids of 2 of a suit to describe very strong hands (strong 2-bids) and that nowadays most bridge players use 2@C as the only strong 2-level suit opening. 

In modern Standard American 2@D, 2@H, and 2@S opening bids are known as weak 2-bids. Here are some example hands for these openings:
^^|
pg| ***** 361 ***** |


cs|3|at|^c{|ih|ps52h86dkqj943cJ63|at|} |n#|t|at|^k{|ih|pd52h86skqj943cJ63}|at| ^s|ih|ps52d86hkqj943cJ63|n^|t|at|

|cs|2|at|^B      {A Weak 2@D opening}^J      {A Weak 2@S opening}^R      {A Weak 2@H opening}

|
pg| ***** 362 ***** |


at|Notice that each of these hands contains only 7 HCP, less than the 10 HCP of an average bridge hand. Each hand also receives 2 long suit points for having a 6-card suit. The 9 total points of each of these hands is not close to enough for a 1-level opening bid (which would require 13 total points).

How can it be right to open the bidding at the 2-level on 
^l   a hand that is not even strong enough for a 1-level opening bid?|
pg| ***** 363 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|Have another look at these 3 hands and consider their potential to win tricks:
|cs|3|n#|5|at|^c{|ih|ps52h86dkqj943cJ63|at|} |n#|t|at|^k{|ih|pd52h86skqj943cJ63|at|} ^s{|ih|ps52d86hkqj943cJ63|n^|t|at|}

Each of these hands is very likely to win 5 tricks without any help from partner if their respective long suits are made to be trump. If another suit is trump, however, each of these hands might not be able to win any tricks at all. These hands may be useful in notrump, especially if partner's hand contains the Ace of the long suit.

|
pg| ***** 364 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{A weak hand with a long suit will usually be able to win several tricks if the long suit is
trump. Such hands tend to win far fewer tricks if the contract is in any other strain.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 365 ***** |


at|There are 40 HCP in the deck so if you are dealt only 7 of these HCP there are a lot of high cards in the other 3 hands. If partner is dealt his fair share of the 33 outstanding HCP there is a good chance that the partnership will be able to win enough tricks to succeed in a 2-level contract with the long suit as trump.

If partner also has a weak hand it is likely that the partnership will fail to win the 8 tricks required by a 2-level opening bid. The weak 2-bid might still work, even if partner also has a weak hand and the contract fails. In this case, it is very likely that the opposing partnership win enough tricks in some other strain to succeed in a game or slam contract of their own.|
pg| ***** 366 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|When you open with a weak 2-bid on hands like these:
|cs|3|n#|5|at|^c{|ih|ps52h86dkqj943cJ63|at|} |n#|t|at|^k{|ih|pd52h86skqj943cJ63|at|} ^s{|ih|ps52d86hkqj943cJ63|n^|t|at|}

you know that your contract may not succeed if partner also has a weak hand. Your partnership will lose points in this case, but the points you lose will be less than the bonus points that the opposing partnership would win if they were to succeed in a game or slam contract.

|
pg| ***** 367 ***** |


cs|2|at|If you pass with these sorts of hands the opposing partnership can start to explore for their best contract at the 1-level. By opening with a weak 2, however, the opponents must start exploration at a higher level of bidding. The weak 2 opening preempts the entire 1-level and part of the 2-level. This will almost always make life harder for the other partnership.

|
pg| ***** 368 ***** |


at|^-{Weak 2-bids are part of a class of bids known as preempts or preemptive openings.
Preempts take up bidding space, making it hard for the opponents to find their best contract.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 369 ***** |


at|Besides 2@D, 2@H, and 2@S, all 3 and 4-level suit openings in our bidding system are also preemptive in nature. It is difficult to rationalize the requirements for such bids without knowing more about how the scoring works in bridge. Bridge scoring is described in the Appendix section of this program, but don't worry about that for now - just try to learn the following definitions for the preemptive openings in our bidding system.|
pg| ***** 370 ***** |


