Here are the definitions for all opening bids. Hands that do not fit any of these should be passed:

|
pg| ***** 377 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{All notrump opening bids promise balanced hands (no voids or singletons and 
at most 1 doubleton). The range of 1NT is 15-17, 2NT is 20-21, and 3NT is 25-27.}

|
pg| ***** 378 ***** |


cs|2|at|{All hands with 22 or more total points unsuitable for a 3NT opening are opened with 2@C.}

|
pg| ***** 379 ***** |


cs|3|at|{Opening bids of 1@C, 1@D, 1@H, and 1@S promise between 13 to 21 total points.}

|
pg| ***** 380 ***** |


cs|1|at|{Opening bids of 1@S and 1@H promise 5 or more cards in the suit named (5-card majors).}

|
pg| ***** 381 ***** |


cs|4|at|{Open your longest suit, even if another suit is stronger or happens to be a 5-card major.
With 2 5-card suits you should open the bidding in the higher-ranking of those 2 suits.}

|
pg| ***** 382 ***** |


cs|2|at|{If a hand has no 5-card major then open the bidding with 1 of your longest minor.
With equal length in both minor suits you should open 1@D with 4-4, but 1@C with 3-3.}

|
pg| ***** 383 ***** |


cs|3|at|{2@D, 2@H, and 2@S openings promise a strong 6-card suit and less than 13 total points.
A strong suit contains at least 2 of the top 3 cards (the Ace, King, and Queen).}

|
pg| ***** 384 ***** |


cs|1|at|{3@C, 3@D, 3@H, and 3@S openings promise a strong 7-card suit and less than 13 total points.
 4@C, 4@D, 4@H, and 4@S openings promise a strong 8-card suit and less than 13 total points.} 

|
