nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|Before you go on to do the exercises at the end of this chapter, here is a review of some of the other important concepts that we have learned about bidding:
|
pg| ***** 386 ***** |


n#|8|cs|4|at|^-{Some contracts award bonus points to a successful declarer. Grand slams
(7-level contracts) are worth the most, followed by small slams (6-level contracts).}

|
pg| ***** 387 ***** |


cs|2|at|{Game contracts of 3NT, 4 of a major (4@S and 4@H), and 5 of a minor (5@D and 5@C),
also award bonus points to a successful declarer, but not as many as slam contracts.}

|
pg| ***** 388 ***** |


cs|3|at|{Partials (contracts below game) award no bonus points to a successful declarer.}

|
pg| ***** 389 ***** |


cs|1|at|{We use Goren's 4-3-2-1 point count to evaluate our hands. Aces are worth 4 high card
points (HCP), Kings are worth 3 HCP, Queens are worth 2 HCP, and Jacks are worth 1 HCP.}

|
pg| ***** 390 ***** |


cs|4|at|{We also use long suit points, adding a point for each 5-card suit and a point for each
additional card in a long suit. Total points = High card points + Long suit points.}

|
pg| ***** 391 ***** |


cs|2|at|{25 total points are usually enough to make 4@S, 4@H or 3NT a good contract. 5@D or 5@C
require 29 total points, small slams 33 total points, and grand slams 37 total points.}

|
pg| ***** 392 ***** |


cs|3|at|{Some bids are artificial - they do not suggest a contract in the strain that they name.
Some bids are forcing - they strongly suggest that partner should not pass.}

|
pg| ***** 393 ***** |


cs|1|at|{Some bids are preemptive - these are deliberate overbids designed more to take away 
bidding space from the opposing partnership than to suggest a contract that rates to succeed.}
^-|
